Shares of Nissan Motor Co Ltd (7201.T) slumped 5 per cent last week, their biggest fall in more than a month, following a report that top shareholder Renault SA may consider lowering its stake in the Japanese automaker. The media reported, recently that Renault may consider lowering its Nissan shareholding as part of plans to separate its electric vehicle business. The French car maker has been pushing ahead with plans to split its electric and combustion-engine businesses in an attempt to catch rivals such as Tesla (TSLA.O) and Volkswagen. -Advertisement- Last week, Renault said all options were on the table for separating the electric vehicle business, including a possible public listing in the second half of 2023. Any plans would be subject to approval from alliance partner Nissan, Thierry Pieton, Renault Finance Chief said, adding the Japanese automaker was “in the loop” as Renault weighed up its options. Renault and Nissan have declined to comment on the report. Shares of Nissan fell to 509.8 yen in Tokyo, marking their biggest one-day decline since early March and underperforming an almost 2 per cent drop in the Nikkei index.